owl:Class.rdfs:comment:
Explanation of the execution of an adduct relation rule. Below is presented an example of empirical compound in JSON (assuming a [particular context](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/marianofl1971/lis/master/OnToology/lis.owl/context/context.jsonld):
~~~~
  {
    "ruleType":"adduct_relation_type",
    "trueValue":"expected",
    "hypothesis": {
      "identifier":315,
      "empiricalCompound": {"mass":517.3172, "rt":19.4689},
      "theoreticalCompound": {"identifier":2628, "name":"PC(O-14:0/2:0)"},
      "adduct":"M+Na"
    },
    "explanation": {
      "coreInformation":"The empirical compound 517.3172@19.4689 is expected to be the theoretical compound PC(O-14:0/2:0) with adduct M+Na, because, for example, the empirical compound 495.3352@19.4689 with adduct M+H may be the theoretical compound PC(O-14:0/2:0) as well."
    }
  }

~~~~
and here, an example in JSON-LD:
~~~~
{
   "@context":
"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/marianofl1971/lis/master/OnToology/lis.owl/context/context.jsonld",

    "ruleType":"adduct_relation_type",
    "trueValue":"expected",
    "hypothesis": {
      "identifier":315,
      "empiricalCompound": {"mass":517.3172, "rt":19.4689},
      "theoreticalCompound": {"identifier":2628, "name":"PC(O-14:0/2:0)"},
      "adduct":"M+Na"
    },
    "explanation": {
      "coreInformation":"The empirical compound 517.3172@19.4689 is expected to be the theoretical compound PC(O-14:0/2:0) with adduct M+Na, because, for example, the empirical compound 495.3352@19.4689 with adduct M+H may be the theoretical compound PC(O-14:0/2:0) as well."
    }
}
~~~~

A certainty level assignment with explanations relates an hypothesis with a certainty level and with an explanation. That is, it is a reification of a ternary relation. Below is presented an example of empirical compound in JSON (assuming a [particular context](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/marianofl1971/lis/master/OnToology/lis.owl/context/context.jsonld):
~~~~
{
    "ruleType":"ionization_rule_type",
    "trueValue":"expected",
    "hypothesis": {
      "identifier":315,
      "empiricalCompound": {"mass":517.3172, "rt":19.4689},
      "theoreticalCompound": {"identifier":2628, "name":"PC(O-14:0/2:0)"},
      "adduct":"M+Na"
    },
    "explanation": {
      "coreInformation":"The empirical compound 517.3172@19.4689 (in an experiment with positive ionization and modifier NH3) is expected to be the theoretical compound PC(O-14:0/2:0) with adduct M+Na, which belongs to the hierarchy GP, GP01, GP0102",
      "additionalInformation":"The empirical compound 495.3352@19.4689 is expected to be the theoretical compound PC(O-14:0/2:0) with adduct M+H, because, for example, the empirical compound 517.3172@19.4689 with adduct M+Na may be the theoretical compound PC(O-14:0/2:0) as well."
    }
}
~~~~
and here, an example in JSON-LD:
~~~~
{
    "@context": "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/marianofl1971/lis/master/OnToology/lis.owl/context/context.jsonld",
    "@type": "https://w3id.org/def/lis#CLAwithExplanations",
      "ruleType":"ionization_rule_type",
    "trueValue":"expected",
    "hypothesis": {
      "identifier":315,
      "empiricalCompound": {"mass":517.3172, "rt":19.4689},
      "theoreticalCompound": {"identifier":2628, "name":"PC(O-14:0/2:0)"},
      "adduct":"M+Na"
    },
    "explanation": {
      "coreInformation":"The empirical compound 517.3172@19.4689 (in an experiment with positive ionization and modifier NH3) is expected to be the theoretical compound PC(O-14:0/2:0) with adduct M+Na, which belongs to the hierarchy GP, GP01, GP0102",
      "additionalInformation":"The empirical compound 495.3352@19.4689 is expected to be the theoretical compound PC(O-14:0/2:0) with adduct M+H, because, for example, the empirical compound 517.3172@19.4689 with adduct M+Na may be the theoretical compound PC(O-14:0/2:0) as well."
    }
}

~~~~
LIS returns an array of certainty level assignments with explanations.

