LIS takes as input an experiment.

A hypothesis is characterised by an empirical compound, a theoretical compound and an adduct. Below is presented an example of empirical compound in JSON (assuming a [particular context](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/marianofl1971/lis/master/OnToology/lis.owl/context/context.jsonld):
~~~~
{
    "identifier": 3,
    "empiricalCompound": {
       "mass": 399.3367,
       "retentionTime": 18.8425
     },
     "theoreticalCompound": {
        "identifier": 32675,
        "name": "L-palmitoylcarnitine"
     },
     "adduct": "M+H"
}
~~~~
and here, an example in JSON-LD:
~~~~
{
    "@context": "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/marianofl1971/lis/master/OnToology/lis.owl/context/context.jsonld",
    "@type": "https://w3id.org/def/lis#Hypothesis",

    "identifier": 3,
    "empiricalCompound": {
       "mass": 399.3367,
       "retentionTime": 18.8425
     },
     "theoreticalCompound": {
        "identifier": 32675,
        "name": "L-palmitoylcarnitine"
     },
     "adduct": "M+H"
}
~~~~

It is a substance that plays the role of modifier in an experiment. The possible modifieres are

- NH3;
- HCOO;
- CH3COO;
- HCOONH3; or
- CH3COONH3

Explanation of the execution of a retention time rule. It can contain evidence for, evidence against or both. Below is presented an example of empirical compound in JSON (assuming a [particular context](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/marianofl1971/lis/master/OnToology/lis.owl/context/context.jsonld):
~~~~
    {
    "ruleType":"retention_time_rule_type",
    "trueValue":"possible",
    "hypothesis": {
      "identifier":496,
      "empiricalCompound": {"mass":282.2563, "rt":31.2616},
      "theoreticalCompound": {"identifier":31512, "name":"10Z-Hexadecenyl acetate"},
      "adduct":"M+H"
    },
    "explanation": {
      "coreInformation":"It is possible that the empirical compound 282.2563@31.2616 is the theoretical compound 10Z-Hexadecenyl acetate with adduct M+H. The theoretical compound is a _WE_OPENPAR_ lipid with 18 carbons and one double bond",
      "evidenceFor":"For example, the compound 280.2402@28.2695 may be the theoretical compound 10E,12E-Hexadecadienyl acetate with adduct M+H, another _WE_OPENPAR_ lipid with 18 carbons and 2 double bonds.",
      "evidenceAgainst":"For example, the compound 280.2402@28.2695 may be the theoretical compound 11-Hexadecynyl acetate with adduct M+H, another _WE_OPENPAR_ lipid with 18 carbons and no double bond."
    }
  }
~~~~
and here, an example in JSON-LD:
~~~~
{
   "@context":
"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/marianofl1971/lis/master/OnToology/lis.owl/context/context.jsonld",

    "ruleType":"retention_time_rule_type",
    "trueValue":"possible",
    "hypothesis": {
      "identifier":496,
      "empiricalCompound": {"mass":282.2563, "rt":31.2616},
      "theoreticalCompound": {"identifier":31512, "name":"10Z-Hexadecenyl acetate"},
      "adduct":"M+H"
    },
    "explanation": {
      "coreInformation":"It is possible that the empirical compound 282.2563@31.2616 is the theoretical compound 10Z-Hexadecenyl acetate with adduct M+H. The theoretical compound is a _WE_OPENPAR_ lipid with 18 carbons and one double bond",
      "evidenceFor":"For example, the compound 280.2402@28.2695 may be the theoretical compound 10E,12E-Hexadecadienyl acetate with adduct M+H, another _WE_OPENPAR_ lipid with 18 carbons and 2 double bonds.",
      "evidenceAgainst":"For example, the compound 280.2402@28.2695 may be the theoretical compound 11-Hexadecynyl acetate with adduct M+H, another _WE_OPENPAR_ lipid with 18 carbons and no double bond."

  }
}
~~~~
